{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659527"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:10:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:10:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20866"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20866"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13741"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79143"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12319"},{"type":"tags","id":"12320"},{"type":"tags","id":"12689"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33071"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with progressive skin tightening over her fingers, hands, and face that has developed over the past two years. On examination, her fingers appear tapered with shiny, taut skin. There is limited range of motion in her finger joints, and her facial expressions are diminished.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA skin biopsy is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histological findings is most characteristic of systemic sclerosis in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased dermal collagen with vascular wall thickening","Dermal neutrophilic infiltrates with leukocytoclasia","Epidermal hyperplasia with parakeratosis","Granulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells","Subepidermal blisters with eosinophilic infiltrates"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased dermal collagen with vascular wall thickening\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the hallmark histological finding in systemic sclerosis. The disease is characterized by excessive collagen deposition in the dermis, along with hyaline thickening of the walls of dermal arterioles and capillaries. Additional histological features include thinning of the epidermis, loss of rete pegs, and atrophy of dermal appendages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in conditions such as sarcoidosis or granulomatous infections, not in systemic sclerosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubepidermal blisters with eosinophilic infiltrates\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of bullous pemphigoid and other autoimmune blistering disorders, not systemic sclerosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermal hyperplasia with parakeratosis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in psoriasis, not systemic sclerosis which actually shows epidermal thinning.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermal neutrophilic infiltrates with leukocytoclasia\u003C/strong\u003E are features of leukocytoclastic vasculitis, not systemic sclerosis which typically shows perivascular T-cell infiltrates in early stages.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn systemic sclerosis, the skin changes begin in the fingers and distal regions of the upper extremities and extend proximally. The progressive fibrosis leads to the clinical features seen in this patient: tapered clawlike fingers, limited joint mobility, and a masklike facial appearance. The vascular changes can lead to decreased blood supply, resulting in cutaneous ulcerations and atrophic changes in the terminal phalanges.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Systemic sclerosis affects multiple organ systems with characteristic skin changes including sclerotic atrophy, fibrosis, and vascular abnormalities.","Histological features of skin in systemic sclerosis include increased dermal collagen, thinning of the epidermis, loss of rete pegs, and hyaline thickening of vessel walls.","Advanced systemic sclerosis can lead to tapered clawlike fingers, limited joint mobility, and facial masking due to skin tightening."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; page 231-233."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20866"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79143"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T17:58:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T17:58:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13741"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96501"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":